  "prompt": "What are the best spell and trap cards in Yu-Gi-Oh?",
  "response": "Okay, defining \"best\" is always tricky in Yu-Gi-Oh! because it depends heavily on the format, the meta (the most popular and effective decks), and your specific deck strategy.  However, I can give you a list of generally powerful and influential Spell and Trap cards that have seen consistent play and are often considered among the best.  I'll categorize them and provide some context:\n\n**Generic Powerhouse Spell Cards (Good in many decks):**\n\n*   **Pot of Prosperity:** (Spell, Normal)  Banish 3 or 6 cards from your Extra Deck face-down; Excavate that many cards from the top of your Deck, add 1 excavated card to your hand, and place the rest on the bottom of your Deck in any order. For the rest of this turn after this card resolves, you cannot draw cards by card effects.\n    *   **Why it's good:** Incredible consistency booster.  Allows you to search for key cards while getting rid of extra deck cards you don't need.  The restriction on drawing for the rest of the turn is a significant drawback, but often worth it.\n\n*   **Triple Tactics Talent:** (Spell, Normal) If your opponent has activated a monster effect during your Main Phase this turn: Activate 1 of these effects;\n    *   \u25cf Draw 2 cards.\n    *   \u25cf Take control of 1 monster your opponent controls until the End Phase.\n    *   \u25cf Look at your opponent's hand, and discard 1 card from it.\n    You can only activate 1 \"Triple Tactics Talent\" per turn.\n    *   **Why it's good:** It punishes your opponent for using monster effects during your turn, providing incredible disruption and/or advantage.  Extremely versatile.\n\n*   **Forbidden Droplet:** (Spell, Quick-Play) Send any number of other cards from your hand and/or field to the GY; choose that many Effect Monsters your opponent controls, and until the end of this turn, their ATK is halved, also they have their effects negated. In response to this card's activation, your opponent cannot activate cards, or the effects of cards, with the same original type (Monster/Spell/Trap) as the cards sent to the GY to activate this card. You can only activate 1 \"Forbidden Droplet\" per turn.\n    *   **Why it's good:** Powerful negation tool that's difficult to respond to.  Bypasses common forms of protection and can weaken the opponent's field significantly.  The cost can be high, but the payoff is often worth it.\n\n*   **Harpie's Feather Duster:** (Spell, Normal) Destroy all Spell and Trap Cards your opponent controls.\n    *   **Why it's good:** Simple, effective, and game-winning. Destroys your opponent's backrow, removing threats and allowing you to push for game.\n\n*   **Raigeki:** (Spell, Normal) Destroy all monsters your opponent controls.\n    *   **Why it's good:**  Like Harpie's Feather Duster, but for monsters.  Board wipes are always powerful.\n\n**Generic Powerhouse Trap Cards:**\n\n*   **Evenly Matched:** (Trap, Normal) At the end of the Battle Phase, if your opponent controls more cards than you do: Make your opponent choose cards they control so they control the same number of cards as you do (they must choose as many as possible), and send the chosen cards to the GY.\n    *   **Why it's good:**  Excellent for going second.  Forces your opponent to give up key resources, leaving them vulnerable. Can be devastating against decks that over-extend.\n\n*   **Infinite Impermanence:** (Trap, Normal) Target 1 face-up monster your opponent controls; negate its effects (until the end of this turn), then, if this card was Set before activation and is being activated on the field, this effect becomes applying until the end of the next turn. If you control no cards, you can activate this card from your hand.\n    *   **Why it's good:**  A hand trap *and* a backrow card. Versatile negation that can disrupt your opponent's plays.  Being able to activate it from the hand is a huge advantage.\n\n*   **Solemn Judgment:** (Trap, Counter) When a Spell/Trap Card is activated, or a monster(s) would be Summoned: Pay half your LP; negate the activation or Summon, and if you do, destroy that card.\n    *   **Why it's good:**  The ultimate \"no.\"  Can negate virtually anything, stopping your opponent's plays dead in their tracks. The life point cost is high, but the control it offers is unmatched.\n\n*   **Skill Drain:** (Trap, Continuous) Negate the effects of all face-up monsters while they are face-up on the field (but negate their effects only during the turn they were Normal Summoned, Set, or Special Summoned).\n    *   **Why it's good:** Can shut down entire decks that rely on monster effects.  However, it also affects your own monsters, so you need to build your deck accordingly.\n\n**Situational but Powerful Cards:**\n\n*   **Super Polymerization:** (Spell, Quick-Play) Discard 1 card; send 2 monsters from either field to the GY, and Special Summon 1 Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck that lists those 2 monsters as Fusion Material. (This Special Summon is treated as a Fusion Summon.) Neither player can activate cards or effects in response to this card's activation.\n    *   **Why it's good:**  A powerful board-breaker that can also be used to extend your own plays. The fact that it can't be responded to is key.  Its effectiveness depends on your Extra Deck and the prevalent monster types in the meta.\n\n*   **Called by the Grave:** (Spell, Quick-Play) Target 1 monster in your opponent's GY; banish it, and negate the effects of monsters with the same original name as that banished monster until the end of the next turn.\n    *   **Why it's good:**  Excellent for negating hand traps and other graveyard effects.  Prevents your opponent from using their key monsters.\n\n**Things to Consider:**\n\n*   **The Banlist:**  The official Forbidden & Limited List changes regularly. Cards that are considered too powerful are often limited (only 1 copy allowed in your deck), semi-limited (2 copies), or forbidden (banned completely).  Make sure to check the current banlist before building your deck.\n*   **Your Deck's Strategy:** The \"best\" card for *you* is the one that best supports your deck's goals.  A card that's amazing in a control deck might be useless in an aggressive combo deck.\n*   **The Meta:**  The most popular and effective decks in the format influence which cards are most valuable. Cards that counter those decks become more important.\n*   **Card Advantage:** Many good cards focus on generating card advantage. Cards that allow you to draw cards, search your deck, or recycle cards from your graveyard are generally valuable.\n*   **Disruption:** Cards that disrupt your opponent's plays, such as negation effects, are crucial for control decks.\n*   **Consistency:** Cards that increase the consistency of your deck, allowing you to find your key cards more reliably, are always good.\n\nThis list is a starting point. The \"best\" cards are constantly evolving as new cards are released and the meta shifts.  Good luck building your decks!\n",
